etymologies: late 17th century (in an earlier sense). From classical Latin quadrigeminus fourfold (from quadri- + geminus twofold, double), in post-classical and scientific Latin also designating a muscle, designating the quadrigeminal bodies, the quadrigeminal tubercles, and the quadrigeminal protuberances, and designating a pulse + -al

definitions: Designating the two pairs of protuberances (the inferior and superior colliculi) of the tectum of the midbrain in mammals; of, relating to, or designating this region of the brain.
Designating or relating to any form of cardiac arrhythmia in which heartbeats (normal or abnormal) occur in groups of four.
